\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 1. INTRODUCTION\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard Road accidents continue to be a major challenge in transportation engineering and public safety. Traditional road safety analysis approaches are mostly descriptive and retrospective, which limits their utility for preventive planning. Civil engineers increasingly require digital tools that can integrate data quality correction, analytics, and prediction in one workflow.\par
\par
\pard This project develops an end-to-end AI-assisted platform focused on:\par
\pard 1. robust preprocessing of accident records,\par
\pard 2. jurisdiction-level risk exploration,\par
\pard 3. machine learning based severity prediction,\par
\pard 4. long-range hotspot forecasting for planning support.\par
\par
\pard The system is implemented as an interactive web application so that domain users without programming experience can directly use filtered dashboards and predictive outputs.\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 2. PROBLEM STATEMENT\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard Accident data is often operationally collected and manually maintained, leading to:\par
\pard 1. inconsistent date formats (`dd/mm/yyyy`, `dd-mm-yyyy`, mixed text),\par
\pard 2. inconsistent time formats (`8.5`, `11.15`, `20.0`, `20:30`),\par
\pard 3. coded fields for collisions/vehicles requiring decoding,\par
\pard 4. variations in day-night tags (`D/N`, `D/ N`, `Day`, `Night`),\par
\pard 5. footer/legend rows embedded with data rows.\par
\par
\pard Because of this, direct model training can produce unreliable trends and misleading outputs. Planning agencies need a system that first standardizes data and then produces interpretable predictions (especially jurisdiction-wise future hotspot ranking).\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 3. OBJECTIVES\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard 1. Build a complete accident analytics and prediction platform for jurisdiction-level planning.\par
\pard 2. Standardize mixed-format records with maximum retention of valid data.\par
\pard 3. Train and compare multiple severity prediction models.\par
\pard 4. Forecast hotspot risk for a 5-year horizon.\par
\pard 5. Provide side-by-side historical and predicted hotspot ranking.\par
\pard 6. Deliver a user-friendly interface for civil engineering practitioners.\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 4. SCOPE OF WORK\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 4.1 In Scope\b0\par
\pard 1. Excel-based accident data ingestion.\par
\pard 2. Cleaning and transformation of structured tabular records.\par
\pard 3. Severity classification and hotspot forecasting.\par
\pard 4. Interactive analytics dashboard and planning interface.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 4.2 Out of Scope\b0\par
\pard 1. Real-time IoT/live traffic feeds.\par
\pard 2. Automatic CCTV/video analytics.\par
\pard 3. Full GIS network simulation.\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 5. STUDY AREA AND DATASET DESCRIPTION\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard Dataset contains jurisdiction-level accident records with key fields:\par
\pard 1. Place/Jurisdiction\par
\pard 2. FIR number\par
\pard 3. Date, time, day/night\par
\pard 4. Collision pattern/type\par
\pard 5. Vehicle type fields\par
\pard 6. Fatal/Grievous/Minor indicators\par
\pard 7. Geometry and infrastructure fields (median/shoulder/footpath/junction)\par
\pard 8. Latitude and longitude\par
\par
\pard The records are suitable for both temporal and spatial analytics once standardized.\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 6. DATA PREPROCESSING AND STANDARDIZATION\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.1 Header Normalization\b0\par
\pard Column variants are canonicalized to expected schema (`D/ N` -> `D/N`, spacing and slash normalization).\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.2 Date Standardization\b0\par
\pard Multi-pass parsing supports slash/hyphen formats and fallback from alternate date components (`Year of Accident`, `Month of the year`, `DAY OF THE WEEK`).\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.3 Time Standardization\b0\par
\pard Time values like `8.5`, `9.3`, `11.15` are converted to hour-minute semantics with fallback parser.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.4 Category Normalization\b0\par
\pard Day/Night values normalized to `D`/`N`; additional readable label generated as `day_night_label`.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.5 Master Reference Decoding\b0\par
\pard Code columns for collision and vehicle classes are decoded through editable reference tables.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.6 Missing Value Handling\b0\par
\pard 1. Numeric columns: median fill.\par
\pard 2. Categorical columns: mode fill with category-safe handling.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 6.7 Data Quality Outcome (Current Tested Run)\b0\par
\pard 1. Rows after cleaning: **1151**\par
\pard 2. Footer rows removed: **34**\par
\pard 3. Key derived columns (`Date`, `year`, `month_num`, `day_of_week`, `hour`, `minute`, `D/N`) available without nulls in tested run.\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 7. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard The application consists of four major user modules and one shared backend layer.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 7.1 User Modules\b0\par
\pard 1. **Home:** summary, KPIs, quick navigation.\par
\pard 2. **Data Manager:** upload/version selection, validation, cleaned view.\par
\pard 3. **Dashboard:** filter-driven maps/charts/hotspots.\par
\pard 4. **Model Training & Prediction:** model benchmarking, severity risk prediction, hotspot forecasting.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 7.2 Backend Components\b0\par
\pard 1. `cleaning.py` – data transformation and feature derivation.\par
\pard 2. `modeling.py` – model training, evaluation, best-model persistence.\par
\pard 3. `forecasting.py` – monthly recursive hotspot forecasting.\par
\pard 4. `viz.py`/`ui.py` – visualization and theme system.\par
\par
\pard ---\par
\par
\pard\qc\sa180\b\fs28 8. METHODOLOGY\b0\fs22\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 8.1 Severity Prediction Workflow\b0\par
\pard 1. Select features from cleaned dataset.\par
\pard 2. Split train/test with stratification.\par
\pard 3. Build preprocessing + model pipelines.\par
\pard 4. Evaluate using CV and hold-out metrics.\par
\pard 5. Save best model for inference in Prediction Studio.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 8.2 Models Evaluated\b0\par
\pard 1. RandomForestClassifier\par
\pard 2. XGBoostClassifier\par
\pard 3. CatBoostClassifier\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 8.3 Evaluation Metrics\b0\par
\pard 1. Accuracy\par
\pard 2. Macro-F1\par
\pard 3. Macro-Recall\par
\pard 4. Confusion Matrix\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 8.4 Hotspot Forecasting Method\b0\par
\pard 1. Aggregate monthly accident counts per jurisdiction.\par
\pard 2. Create continuous month timelines (missing months filled with 0).\par
\pard 3. Generate lag and seasonality features:\par
\pard    - lag_1, lag_2, lag_3\par
\pard    - rolling_3\par
\pard    - month sin/cos\par
\pard    - trend index\par
\pard 4. Train GradientBoostingRegressor.\par
\pard 5. Forecast recursively for 60 months.\par
\par
\pard\sa120\b 8.5 Historical vs Predicted Comparison\b0\par
\pard Hotspot page supports:\par
\pard 1. **Historical (Actual Data):** rank by observed count for selected month-year.\par
\pard 2. **Predicted (AI Forecast):** rank by model-estimated count/risk for selected period.\par
\par
